6 ^ WORKER ■ ISSU E NO. 48 

MALTREATMENT OF BABIES 

In their anthropological performance on infant abuse, Hilgendorf 
and Chisholm reveal the processes in which innumerable infants come 
to the threshold of death through extramarital societal intercourse. 
Numerous aspects of modern motherhood are unravelled from numerous 
dimensions of their ethnographic experiment on preventing infant 
death on the Tallowalesu village, Fiji. With reference to the 
continental essence of women as mothers, the two anthropologists 
described the side-effects of Papa-ride or husband removal from the 
woman's household in order to induce abortion. The bedimmest effects
